WEBVTT

00:00.120 --> 00:04.040
Are we the only living things in the entire universe?

00:04.040 --> 00:08.800
The observable universe is about 90 billion light-years in diameter.

00:08.800 --> 00:15.280
There are at least 100 billion galaxies, each with 100 to 1000 billion stars.

00:15.280 --> 00:20.720
Recently, we've learned that planets are very common too, and there are probably trillions

00:20.720 --> 00:25.700
and trillions of habitable planets in the universe, which means there should be lots

00:25.700 --> 00:29.280
of opportunity for life to develop and exist, right?

00:29.280 --> 00:30.280
But where is it?

00:30.280 --> 00:33.680
Shouldn't the universe be teeming with spaceships?

00:33.680 --> 00:41.800
Let's take a step back.

00:41.800 --> 00:46.520
Even if there are alien civilizations in other galaxies, there's no way we'll ever know

00:46.520 --> 00:47.520
about them.

00:47.520 --> 00:53.120
Basically, everything outside of our direct galactic neighborhood, the so-called local group, is

00:53.120 --> 00:58.220
pretty much out of our reach forever because of the expansion of the universe.

00:58.220 --> 01:02.940
Even if we had really fast spaceships, it would literally take billions of years to reach

01:02.940 --> 01:08.220
these places, traveling through the emptiest areas in the universe.

01:08.220 --> 01:10.680
So let's focus on the Milky Way.

01:10.680 --> 01:12.940
The Milky Way is our home galaxy.

01:12.940 --> 01:15.720
It consists of up to 400 billion stars.

01:15.720 --> 01:17.840
That's a lot of stars.

01:17.840 --> 01:22.220
Counting one per second, it would take you 100 lifetimes to count them all.

01:22.220 --> 01:27.340
There are about 20 billion sun-like stars in the Milky Way, and estimates suggest that

01:27.340 --> 01:31.820
a fifth of them have an Earth-sized planet in its habitable zone, the area with conditions

01:31.820 --> 01:33.860
that enable life to exist.

01:33.860 --> 01:39.800
If only 0.1% of those planets harbored life, there would be one million planets with life

01:39.800 --> 01:40.940
in the Milky Way.

01:40.940 --> 01:43.060
But wait, there's more.

01:43.060 --> 01:46.220
The Milky Way is about 13 billion years old.

01:46.220 --> 01:50.080
In the beginning, it would not have been a good place for life, because things exploded

01:50.080 --> 01:51.080
a lot.

01:51.080 --> 01:55.140
But after 1 to 2 billion years, the first habitable planets were born.

01:55.140 --> 01:59.840
Earth is only 4 billion years old, so there have probably been trillions of chances for

01:59.840 --> 02:02.480
life to develop on other planets in the past.

02:02.480 --> 02:07.060
If only a single one of them had developed into a space-traveling supercivilization, we

02:07.060 --> 02:08.980
would have noticed by now.

02:08.980 --> 02:11.740
What would such a civilization look like?

02:11.740 --> 02:13.660
There are three categories.

02:13.660 --> 02:19.380
A Type I civilization would be able to access the whole energy available on its planet.

02:19.380 --> 02:24.580
In case you're wondering, we're currently around 0.73 on the scale, and we should reach

02:24.580 --> 02:28.200
Type I sometime in the next couple of hundred years.

02:28.200 --> 02:33.800
Type II would be a civilization capable of harnessing all of the energy of its home star.

02:33.800 --> 02:38.680
This would require some serious science fiction, but it is doable in principle.

02:38.680 --> 02:44.120
Just like the Dyson Sphere, a giant complex surrounding the sun would be conceivable.

02:44.120 --> 02:49.360
Type III is a civilization that basically controls its whole galaxy and its energy.

02:49.360 --> 02:53.560
An alien race this advanced would probably be godlike to us.

02:53.560 --> 02:58.240
But why should we be able to see such an alien civilization in the first place?

02:58.240 --> 03:03.320
If we were to build generation spaceships that could sustain a population for around 1,000

03:03.320 --> 03:07.780
years, we could colonize the whole galaxy in 2 million years.

03:07.780 --> 03:08.780
Looks like a long time.

03:08.780 --> 03:11.840
But remember, the Milky Way is huge.

03:11.840 --> 03:16.840
So if it takes a couple of million years to colonize the entire galaxy, and there are possibly

03:16.840 --> 03:22.160
millions if not billions of planets that sustain life in the Milky Way, and these other life

03:22.160 --> 03:28.780
forms have had considerably more time than we've had, then where are all the aliens?

03:28.780 --> 03:32.780
This is the Fermi Paradox, and nobody has an answer to it.

03:32.780 --> 03:34.780
But we do have some ideas.

03:34.780 --> 03:36.840
Let's talk about filters.

03:36.840 --> 03:41.840
A filter in this context represents a barrier that is really hard for life to overcome.

03:41.840 --> 03:44.840
They come in various degrees of scary.

03:44.840 --> 03:49.840
There are great filters and we have passed them.

03:49.840 --> 03:53.840
Maybe it is way harder for complex life to develop than we think.

03:53.840 --> 03:59.080
The process allowing life to begin hasn't yet been completely figured out, and the conditions

03:59.080 --> 04:01.900
required may be really complicated.

04:01.900 --> 04:07.160
Maybe in the past, the universe was way more hostile, and only recently have things cooled

04:07.160 --> 04:09.540
down to make complex life possible.

04:09.540 --> 04:14.440
This would also mean that we may be unique, or at least one of the first, if not the first

04:14.440 --> 04:16.840
civilization in the entire universe.

04:16.840 --> 04:21.700
Two, there are great filters, and they are ahead of us.

04:21.700 --> 04:23.960
This one would be really, really bad.

04:23.960 --> 04:28.100
Maybe life on our level exists everywhere in the universe, but it gets destroyed when

04:28.100 --> 04:32.260
it reaches a certain point, a point that lies ahead of us.

04:32.260 --> 04:38.020
For example, awesome future technology exists, but when activated, it destroys the planet.

04:38.020 --> 04:42.900
The last words of every advanced civilization would be, this new device will solve all of

04:42.900 --> 04:45.180
our problems once I push this button.

04:45.180 --> 04:50.340
If this is true, then we are closer to the end than the beginning of human existence.

04:50.340 --> 04:56.620
Or maybe there is an ancient type 3 civilization that monitors the universe, and once civilization

04:56.620 --> 05:01.140
is advanced enough, it gets eliminated in an instant.

05:01.140 --> 05:05.860
Maybe there is something out there that it would be better not to discover.

05:05.860 --> 05:08.020
There is no way for us to know.

05:08.020 --> 05:10.940
One final thought, maybe we are alone.

05:10.940 --> 05:14.900
Right now, we have no evidence that there is any life besides us.

05:14.900 --> 05:15.900
Nothing.

05:15.900 --> 05:18.940
The universe appears to be empty and dead.

05:18.940 --> 05:22.100
No one sending us messages, no one answering our calls.

05:22.100 --> 05:28.420
We may be completely alone, trapped on a tiny moist mud ball in an eternal universe.

05:28.420 --> 05:29.820
Does that thought scare you?

05:29.820 --> 05:32.980
If it does, you are having the correct emotional reaction.

05:32.980 --> 05:38.140
If we let life on this planet die, perhaps there will be no life left in the universe.

05:38.140 --> 05:40.340
Life will be gone, maybe forever.

05:40.340 --> 05:45.420
If this is the case, we just have to venture to the stars and become the first type 3 civilization

05:45.420 --> 05:49.460
to keep the delicate flame of life existing and to spread it until the universe breathes

05:49.460 --> 05:52.820
its final breath and vanishes into oblivion.

05:52.820 --> 05:58.780
The universe is too beautiful not to be experienced by someone.

